                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13178770" author="jamezp" created="Thu, 17 Mar 2016 19:16:49 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;This should actually be a requirement and not an option. Reason being is the reaper thread that checks whether a server is down is never cancelled during this goal. This means that if the server is shutdown and another processes is started via other means the reaper may kill issue a shutdown on the new process.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Do note too it might be possible to keep compatibility by killing the reaper if the process is destroyed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13195372" author="jamezp" created="Thu, 21 Apr 2016 12:32:22 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;After more thought on this I&apos;m going to remove the shutdown hook from the goal. This means that process will continue to run unless the &lt;tt&gt;shutdown&lt;/tt&gt; goal is also executed. Or the container is shutdown from CLI or some other management operation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For reference the &lt;a href=&quot;https://maven.apache.org/plugin-developers/common-bugs.html#Using_Shutdown_Hooks&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;maven plugin documentation&lt;/a&gt; does have a good point of IDE&apos;s running maven and how shutdown hooks might not be executed when expected. For this reason the container process will no longer be destroyed at shutdown.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
